{"/service/ndnp/deu/batch_deu_groot_ver01/data/sn87062224/0051415689A/1957122701/0122.xml":{"full_text":"CHURCHES IN MILFORD\nAvenue Methodist Church\nRobert E. Green, Pastor\nSUNDAY. DECEMBER 29\n9:00 a. m., Methodist Men's Hour,\nWKSB Radio Station.\n9:45 a. m., Church School. Wil\nson Sockrider, Supt. Cbas. Lur\nwick, Assistant Supt., with Miss\nRuth Benoit, Director of Christian\nEducation supervising. Classes with\nBible graded lesson series for all\nages. Newcomers afid visitors are\nalways welcome. Servicemen and\ntheir families will find a hearty,\ngreeting awaiting them.\n10:46 a. m.. Nursery. Hostesses:\nMrs. Clarence Jester, Mrs. Ben\nBridgers. Parents attending the\neleven o'clock service may leave\ntheir small children in the nursery.\n11:00 a. m., Service of Worship.\nStudent Recognition Day. Over 40\ncollege, university and Prep School\nStudents from Avenue Church have\nbeen invited to participate in the\nservice. Sermon subject: \"For All\nOur Years!'' The Sanctuary Choir\ndirected hy Mrs. A. C. Davidson\nwith Margaret Hart Clark, organist\nwll slug the anthem; \"The King of\nLove Proclaim\", by Stickler. Elea\nnor Lurwick, soprano soloist with\nchoir. The Crusade Choir directed\nby Mrs, Helen Hickman will sing\nthe anthem: \"Fairest Lord Jesus\",\nwith descant by Volkslieder. Bari\ntone solo, by Melvin James. Church\nGoing Families Stay Longer To\ngether.\nRegular Church Attendance\nbrings renewed hope, and a grow\ning faith. The Answer Is God. See\nYou In Church Sunday.\n6:30 p. m., Methodist Youth Fel\nlowship. All Youth Invited to par\nticipate.\nTuesday. December 31, 11:00\nm.. United New Year's Service will\nbe conducted in the First Baptist\nChurch, Milford, sponsored by the\nMilford Ministerium.\nThursday, 7:00 p. m., Chapel,\nChancel and Crusade Choir.\nThursday, 8:00 p. m., Sanctuary\nChoir rehearsal.\nSt, John's Catholic Church\nRev. John A. Corrigan, Pastor\nSUNDAY, DECEMBER 29\nToday, the Sunday within the\noctave of the feast of Christmas,\nj^he Masses will be at 7:30; 9:00;\nand 11:00 a. m. At the last Mass\n4he Christmas music will bo re\npeated.\nOn Sunday evening at 7:30 there\nwill be a party in the Church hall\n1er the teenagers from not only\nSt. John's but also all the neigh\nboring parishes\u2014Holy Cross, St.\nEdmond's, St. Michael's, Our Lady\nof Lourdes, St. Bernadette's, and\nSt. Benedict's. A trio from St. Ber\nnadette's will furnish music for\nthe entertainment.\nBecause of the holidays, Mass on\neach morning will be at 8:00 except\non Wednesday and Friday.\nOn Wednesday, New Year's day\nthe Masses will be at the same\ntimes as on Sunday\u20147:30; 9:00;\nand 11:00 a. m.\nOn Friday, the first Friday of\nthe New Year, a new custom will\nbe started. There will be no Mass\non Friday morning; instead, the\nMass will be offered at 7:30 in the\nevening. This change is being\nmade to enable a larger number\nof the parishioners to follow the\npractice of receiving Holy Com\nmunion on the first Friday of each\nmonth. Confessions will be heard\non Friday night from 6:30.\nBecause of the holidays there\nwill be no evening devotions on\nWednesday; nor will there be any\nclasses in religion this week.\nConfessions will be heard on\nSaturday evening beginning at\n7:30.\nSt. Bernadette's Catholic Church\nDixon liberty Streets, Harringtei.\nRev. John A. Corrigan. Pastor\nSUNDAY. DECEMBER 29\nSunday'morning Mass will be at\n9:30. Confessions will be heard be\nfore the Mass.\nOn Wednesday, New Year's Day,\nthere will be a Mass at 9:30.\nf\nChristian Science Society\nBranch of Th\u00ab First Church of Christ\nScionlist In Boston, Mass.\nSUNDAY, DECEMBER 29\nThe subject of the Lesson-Ser\nmon In First Church of Christ.\nScientist, 1201 Van Buren Street,\nWilmington, First Church of Christ.\nScientist, V. I. A. Building, Reho\nboth Beach, Christian Science So\nciety, 301 South Walnut Street, Mil\nford and Christian Science Society,\nNew Century Club, Dover, Sunday,\nDecember 29, 1957, will be \"Chris\ntian Science\".\nMorning Service and Sunday\nSchool are at 11:00 a. m.; Dover,\nSunday School. 9:30 a. m.; Wilm\nington, Evening Service, 7:30.\nt\nEPISCOPAL DIOCESE OF\nDELAWARE\nSunday services at Delaware Re\nsort Churches:\nSt. Martin's, Bethany Beach\u20148\nand 10:30 a. m.\nAll Saints' Church, Rehoboth\nBeach\u2014S, 9:30 and 11 a. m.\nSt. Peter's. Lewes\u20148 and U a.\nm.\nYour church is with you\u2014even\non your vacation. Are you with\nthe church? Don't neglect your duty\nto worship God every Sunday in\nHis church while you are away\nthis summer.\nt\nChrist Church (Episcopal)\nRev. Joseph S. Hinks. Rector\nSUNDAY. DECEMBER 29\n7:30 a. m.. Holy Communion.\n9:45 a. m., Church School and\nKindergarten Services and Ses\nsions.\n11:00 a. ra.. Morning Prayer and\nFestival of Lessons.\nBethel A. M. E. Church\nRev. J. W. Beavers, Pastor\nSUNDAY. DECEMBER 29\n11 a. m. Morning Worship.\n1:30 p. m. Sunday School.\n6:30 p. m. Allen Christian En\ndeavor League,\n8 p. m One hour service.\n9:00 a. m.. Methodist Men's Hour\n9:45 a. m., Caurch School. Joha\nCalvary Methodist Church\nKev. r. ucugias Milbury, Minister\nSUNDAY, DECEMBER 29\n1\n\nover WKSB Radio Station.\nWilkins, General Supt.; Roy Petty\njohn, Asst. Supt. Why not spend the\nlast Sunday of the old year in Sun\nday School.' We have just the class\nto suit you. Come and Study God's\nWord with us.\n11:00 a. m.. There fs a nursery\nwhere you may leave your small\nchildren, while you worship with\nus in the Sanctuary. Hostess: Mrs.\nJo Ann Harrington.\n11:00 a. m., Morning Worship. Mr.\nMilbury will speak on \"The M\u00e0ster\nCalls For You.\" Students will help\nin the service. The music will be\nfurnished by the Adult Choir under\nthe direction of Mrs. Marie Gilten\nboth and acompanied at the Con\nsole of the organ by Mrs. Alice\nBarber. The Friendly Greeters are\nMrs. Mary Kimmey and Mrs. Lettie\nArgo. The Ushers are William\nCraig, Preston Kenton, Townsend\nHolston, Carl Gobay and Charles\nWest.\n6:30 p. m., Intermediate and\nSenior MYF.\n2:30 p. m., to 5:00 p. m., and\n7:00 to 9:00 p. m., Open House at\nthe parsonage, 206 S. E. Front St.\nActivities for the Week\nPrayer Group: Monday, 1:30 p.\nm., at the home of Mrs. Mildred\nO'Day, Marshall St.\nTuesday, 2:00 p. m., at the home\nof Mrs. Lula Webb, 420 S. Wash\nington St.\nThursday. 2:00 p. m., at the home\nof Mrs. Viola Leverage, Lynch\nHeights.\nPrayer Time: Monday evening,\n7-7:30 p. m.. Prayer group for men\nwith Mr. Milbury in the Church\nstudy.\nWednesday, 9-9:30 a. m., in the\nChurch Chapel with Mr. Milbury.\nAll welcome.\nTuesday, 11:00 p. ra., Watch Night\nservice at Milford Baptist Church.\nThursday, 7:00 p. m., Junior Choir\nrehearsal; 7:30 p. m.. Adult Choir\nrehearsal.\nFriday, Brotherhood Class will\nmeet, at 8:00 p. m.\nM^iiwood Methodist Church\nRev. F. Douglas Milbury, Ministar\nSUNDAY, DECEMBER 29\nChurch School, 10:00 a. m.\nPilgrim Holiness Church\nRev Loon O. Hynson, Pas'or\nSUNDAY, DECEMBER 29\n9:45 a. m. Sunday School, Hu\nbert Passwaters, Supt. William E.\nWiley, Ass't. Supt.\nIt is a pleasure to welcome you\ninto our services. On this, the last\nSunday of the year, we can say\nthat this has been a good year, as\nwe met in the Sunday School from\nweek to week. Our Sunday School\nhas continued to make solid pro\ngress this year and the credit be\nlongs to you whose coming makes\nit possible.\nWe wish to welcome you to every\nsession of the Sunday School in\nthe New Year.\nMeet with us this Sunday. All\nof our friends are given a hearty\nwelcome to this day's services.\n11:00 a. m. Morning Worship.\nThe worship hour gives to us the\nopportunity to draw near to God\nand feed our inner man on the\n\"bread which cometh from heav\nen\". Man cannot live by physical\nbread alone but by the word of\nGod.\nThe pastor will speak on the\nsubject, \"They Were Afraid at\nChristmas.\"\n7:00 p. m. Youth Service, Janet\nSchelhouse, President.\nThe\nPastor will preach the evening\nmessage.\nNew Year's Eve: Union Service\nat the First Baptist Church, Mil\nford, from 11:00 p. in. to midnight.\nNew Year's Day: All day Youth\nrally at the Lulu Ross Elementary\nSchool. Services at 10:30 a. m.,\n2:30 and 6:45 p. m. All are wel\ncomed.\nf\nSh Paul Methodist Church\nRev. Roland Grant, Pastor\nSUNDAY, DECEMBER 29\n11:00 a. m. Worship Service.\n1:00 p. m. Church School.\n7:00 p. m. Methodist Youth Fel\nlowship.\n8:00 p. tn., Monday: Mission of\nFinance Meeting,\n8:00 p. m., Wednesday: Prayer\nService.\nFriday 7:30-10:00 p. m., Recrea\ntion Open House will bo held every\nFriday night at St. Paul Methodist\nChurch. Milford. Boys and girls,\nage 12-18 and adults, who like time\nout for recreation and fun are wel\ncome. Help us to help the hoys and\ngirls of this community. Sponsored\nby the Commission on Education.\nFelton Methodist Charge\nLarry S. Renner, Minister\nSUNDAY. DECEMBER 29\ntfanshlps Church\nWorship Service, 9:30 a. m.\nSunday School, 10:30 a. m..\nFelton Church\nSunday School, 9:45 a. m.\nWorship Service, 10:60 a. m.\nFlola Church\nSunday School, 10:00 a. m.\nWorship Service. 7:00 p. m.\nChurch of the Nazarene\nRev. Mrs. Lorraine Ottinger\nHarrington, Delaware\nSUNDAY. DECEMBER 29\n9:45 a. m. Sunday School. Ben\nDean. Superintendent.\n11:00 a. m. Morning Worship\nService. Sermon by Pastor.\n7:00 p. m. N. Y. P. S. Program.\n7:30 p. m. Evangelistic Service.\n7:30 p. m., Wednesday. Prayer\nf\nChurch of God of Prophecy\nMarshall Street\nRev. John E. Robert*. Pastor\nSUNDAY. DECEMBER 29\nSunday School, 10 o'clock.\n'caching at 11 o'clock.\nSunday night services, 7:30.\nW. M. B-, Wednesday night, 7:30.\nPresbyterian Church\nHarry J. Jaeger. Th.B., Minister\nSUNDAY, DECEMBER 29\nA cartoon we saw still gives a\nchuckle. Fellow went into a gar\nage for some motor repair. Can\nyou fix it?\" he asked the mechanic.\n\"Sure\", was the reply, \"we can fix\nthe thing. Say how do you open\nthe hood?' Did you ever get the\nfeeling you'd like to fix up a badly\n'\u00abn down year in the last few days.\nBut you don't know where to be\ngin, so you decide on a new leaf for\nthe new year and then it's\nmore or less the same story all\nover? There is only One who can\nkeep life in repair and make the\nroad straight. It isn't you and it\nisn't me. It's God.\nServices Sunday, wonderful as\nusual. Youth Choir rehearses at 9\na. m\u201e Sunday School at 9:45. The\nMorning Service is at 11 a. m.\nWestminster Fellowships are at\n6:30 and the evening service is at\n7:45.\nThe Community Watch Night Ser\nvice, Tuesday at 11 p. m., at the\nBaptist Church. Hope to see you\nthere.\nOn Thursday, January 2nd, there\nwill be a preparatory service at\n7:30 looking forward to Com\nmunion which will be observed at\n11 a. m., Sunday, January 5th. At\n8:30, Thursday, again January 2nd,\nthe choir will meet for its first\nrehearsal with our new director\nof music, Mrs. Norma Heyde.\nReformation Lutheran Church\nServices held each Sunday in the Grange\nHall on S. E. Second Street\nThe Rev. John M. Scherch, Pastor\nSUNDAY, DECEMBER 29\nChurch World News, WKSB, 8:15\na. m.\nThe Sunday Church School, 9:45\na. m.\nThe Service of Worship, 11:00\na. m.\nThe. Annual Meeting of the con\ngregation will be held on Wednes\nday, January 15th, at 7:30 p. m.,\nin the Grange Hall. This is advance\nnotice so that members may set\naside that evening on their calen\ndars.\nThe catechetical classes will re\nsume on Saturday, January 4th, at\n10 and 11 a. m.\nCome Worship With Us As We\nGather Together In Our Lord's\nName.\nFirst Baptist Church\nRev. Thomas G. Harris, Pastor\nSUNDAY, DECEMBER 29\n9:45 a. m. Church School class\nes for the whole family; don't let\ndown on the last Sunday of 1957;\ncome with a car-load!\n11:00 a. m. Morning Worship\nService: the sermon will be: \"A\nYear of Development and Delin\nquency.\" Worship as a family this\nweek.\n6:30 p. m. Training Union with\nMr. Charles Jacobs.\n7:30 p. in. Evening Evangelistic\nHour: special music, congrega\ntional favorites, and the message\nof the night. \"Twentieth Century\nFaith.\"\nServicemen and their families\nare always welcome.\nThere is a nursery where you\nmay leave your little ones while\nyou worship with us.\nNEW YEAR'S EVE will find our\nChurch playing host to the church\nes of Milford for the Annual Watch\nnight Community Service. This\nservice will be one of testimony,\nprayer, and song, both congrega\ntional and special.\n8:00 p. m., Wednesday: Prayer\nand Bible Study Hour.\n\"I can do all things through\nChrist which strengthened me.\"\nPhil. 4:13.\nThe public is cordially invited\nto attend these services.\nMillville Methodist Church\nREV. MELVIN E. WHEATIEY, SR., Pastor\nBible School at 10 a. m. Lesson:\n\"Brothers Through Christ.\" That\n\"Brotherhood\"\nHarry Dale, general superintend\nent\nbadly.\nneeded\nWorship service at 11 a. m. Ser\nmon: \"Christmas Always 1 Why\nNot?\" I say again\nOur last service for 1957. Wise man\nsaid; \"Better is the end\u2014than the\nbeginning\"\u2014that's true of your\nlife at the year's end. Should be\u2014\nis it?\nMusic by seniors. Mrs. Nellie\nBanks organist. Youth choirs, Mrs.\nRuth Hickman, director, Miss Ann\nHickman, pianist.\nCome thou with us.\nWhy Not?\"\nWhitesville Charge\nClarence B. Wilkins, Pastor\nBethany\nChurch\nH. W. Lingb, Supt.\nChurch School Picnic, Wednes\nday, July 11th, at 6 9. m., at\nfrap Pond.\nBetbesda\nChurch School, 1:30 p. m., Mrs.\nRuth Smith, Supt.\nDivine\nehool, 10:00 a. m., Mr.\nWorship, pastor, 2:30\np. m.\nLine\nChurch School, 10:00 a. m., Mr.\nHarold White, Supt\nDivine Worship, pastor, 11:00\nr*.\nMt. Enon Baptist Church\nRev. D. A. Downing, Pester\nSUNDAY. DECEMBER 29\nSunday School 10:30.\nWorship Service, 11:30 a. m. and\np. m.\nBYPU and BP\u00dc, 6:30 p. m.\nWednesday evening from 8 to\n1:30, choir rehearsal.\nThursday prayer praise 8 to 9.\nJoin the Church Crusade with\nas for Church Attendance. God Is\nour Strength.\nHebron Methodist Church\nWalter G. Barlow, Pastor\nThe next service scheduled for\nat this service.\nHebron Church is Sunday, Decem\nber 29. at 2 p. m. This will be a\nNew Year's Service. The Pastor\nwil have for the Sermon Subject,\n\"Things To Come As Revealed For\nUs In the Bible\".\nWe will be glad to welcome you\nm\nmk\nm\n\nHlipiE\n\nv.\nml\nm\nUte\u00bb. 3**\nV;\n1\nAERIAL SHOT OF LULU M. ROSS SCHOOL Shown above is a complete aerial view of Milford's newest\nschool, the Lulu M. Ross, which was dedicated with impressive exercises on Sunday, December 15th.\nOBITUARY\nSACHER\nJohn Sacher, age 84 years, died\nat Bremerton, Washington, Dec. 14,\n1957, and was buried at Bremer\nton. He lived near Greenwood, Del.,\nfor 28 years before moving to\nWashington to live with his sister.\nHe is survived by one sister and 3\nbrothers, Mrs. Pete Emel of Brem\nerton, Henry of Bremerton, and\nLewis of Greenwood, and Albert\nof Camden, Del.\nON WAY OUT\nRICHMOND, Va. (\u00c6>)\u2014 Jhis\ncity, which has many equestrian\nstatues, says statues of future he\nroes must be on foot\u2014or replaced\nby something like a memorial ca\n*rilllon.\nPlanning officials says the age\nof equestrian statues ended when\ntanks, planes and other mechanical\ndevices replaced the horse. And\nthey don't think a Patton on a\ntank, a Doolittle in a plane or a\nMacArthur in a PT boat would be\nappropriate on a memorial boule\nvard.\nTraffic officials are expected to\nbe happy about this.\nChurch of God\nRev. W. Edwin Tull. Pastor\nSUNDAY. DECEMBER 29\n9:45 a. m., Sunday School. Class\nes for all ages. Teachers who are\ninterested in your mental and spir\nitual development. Lessons which\nare Bible-centered. \"Come to Sun\nday School today and reap rich re\nwards tomorrow\" as well as today.\nLaben A. Benton, General Superin\ntendent; Leonard Wisseman, As\nsistant Superintendent.\n11:00 a. m., Morning Worship.\n\"In the quietness of this hour you\ncan experience Christ anew.\"\nhymns, scripture re\u00e0ding, prayers,\nand sermon by the pastor will help\nyou to be a better Christian. You\nneed the encouragement and re\nnewed faith which comes from\nworshipping in God's house with\nfellow Christians. This service will\nbe broadcast over WKSB Radio\nStation.\n6:30 p. m.. Young People's Choir\npractice.\n7:00 p. m., Evening Evangelistic\nService. We invite you to come wor\nship with us. Join in singing of\ngospel songs and hymns. Receive\ninspiration from \u00a3he special sing\ning. Hear the pastor preach a ser\nmon from the Word of God. Visitors\nare always welcome to our services.\nThe\nWeek-Day Activities\nMonday, 1:30 p. m., Women's\nPrayer Meeting.\nTuesday evening, Community\nNew Year's Watch service at the\nFirst Baptist Church.\nThursday, 7:00 p. m., Weekly\nOfficers and Teachers' Meeting. At\n8:00 p. m., the Children's Church,\nLamplighters Club, Young People's\nService, and Adult Bible Study.\nSaturday, 6:00 a. m.. Men's\nPrayer Meeting.\nMilford Church of the Nazarene\nRev. Edward M. Gladden\nSUNDAY, DECEMBER 29\n9:45 a. m., Sunday School. Class\nes for all aged groups. Bring your\nchildren and let them learn of God\nand his beloved son, Jesus, early in\ntheir lives, that they may have\nChrists' guidance as t\u00f9ey grow up.\nCharles Bradley, Supt.\n11:00 a. m.. Morning Prayer and\nWorship. Come to Church.\nThursday, 7:45 p. m., Prayer\nmeeting. Fellowship with one an\nother in prayer. Makes our lives\nmuch easier to live. Burdens are\nnot so heavy. Troubles are not so\nbad when we all join together\nwith God.\n\"Hear my prayer, O Lord, and let\nmy cry come unto thee. Hide not\nthy face from me in the day when\nI am in trouble; incline thine ear\nunto me; in the day when I call,\nanswer me speedily. Psalm 102:1-2.\nBarratt's Chapel\nR\u00ab\u00bb. LeRoy Jones. Pastor\nSUNDAY, DECEMBER 29\n2:30 p. m.. Worship Service. Try\nour welcoum\nSiloam A. M. E. Church\nSLAUGHTER NECK\nRev, B. Washington, Pastor\n10:00 a. m. Sunday School. Mrs\nBstella Felton, Superintendent\n11:00 m. Morning Worship.\nSermon by pastor.\nWednesday night. Song and\nPraise Service.\nCome and worship with us.\nThe Bible Presbyterian Church\nRev. John W. Fuhon, Pastor\nPocahontas Hall\nS. E. Second and Washington\nMilford, Delaware\n9:46 a. m., Sunday SchooL\n11:00 a. m.. Morning Worship\n7:30 p. m.. Evening Worship.\nf\nPhiladelphia Federal Reserve Bank\nAsks ff JVhat of 1958?\"\nA business outlook statement for\n1958 need not and should not be a\nrecitative of doleful statistics; nei\nther .should it be an aria of un\nfounded optimism. Nevertheless,\nany such statement cannot well be\nanything other than an appraisal\nof probabilities erected upon \u00e0\nfoundation of assumptions.\nWe shall assume, to begin with,\nthat international tensions will re\ntain their status quo, that Nature\nwill continue to be good to us, that\neveryone will recognize the falli\nbility of forecasters, and that basic\nunderlying economic, political, a,nd\nsocial forces will influence business\nmore than the forecasters influence\nbusiness.\nAt this writing (mid-December)\ntwo Russian and no American \"sat\nellities\" are circling the globe, the\nNATO conference in Paris is just\ngetting under way, and business\nactivity in the world's leading in\ndustrial countries is somewhat less\nexuberant than a year earlier.\nIn the United States, numerous\nbarometers of business activity are,\nor were quite recently, lower than\nthey were at the beginning of last\nyear. Among them might be cited\nthe Federal Reserve Board's index\nof industrial production, freight-car\nloadings, weekly hours of industrial\nemployment, and department-store\nsales. Contrary-wise, a number of\nbusiness indices, particularly those\nexpressed in dollar values, are\nhigher. Among these are total re\ntail trade, business inventories, dis\nposable personal income, and gross\nnational product\u2014which reflects the\ndollar value of total output of all\ngoods and services, including gov\nernment services.\nIn boardrooms, club cars, on col\nlege campuses, and even in barber\nshops, there is apprehensive talk\nabout the business outlook for 1958.\nThe habitual pessimists and re\ncently converted pessimists readily\ncite numerous business indices\nwhich, although higher than a year\nago, have recently ceased rising or\nhave turned down. Pessimists point\nthe finger at the all-commodity in\ndex of wholesale prices, business\ninvestment in new plant and equi\nment, corporate profits, the flow of\npersonal income, and the trend of\nsecurities prices on the stock mar\nket. In adidtion, the statistically\nerudite p\u00e9ssimists mention dimin\nishing flows of new orders, declin\ning backlogs of orders, and appar\nent evidence of more cautious spen\nding on the part of consumers. And\nthe daily press reports unfavorable\nbusiness news items seemingly\nmore frequently than favorable\nnews.\nAll these developments have pro\nduced a psychological chill\u2014an un\ncomfortable feeling that at long\nlast a business recession of sorts\nmay be at hand. The optimists are\nquick to point out that despite some\nadverse reports, business is still\nKent Home Doings\nFrom; RUTH ADAMS\nKent County Home Demonstration\nAgent\n1958 Food Supplies\nFood supplies next year are ex\npected to be large, almost as large\nas those of 1957, according to in\nformation received from the U. S.\nDepartment of Agriculture.\nA strong demand for food from\nconsumers also is expected next\nyear, following the spending pat\ntern that has marked recent high\nemployment years.\nRemainder of the report on the\nfood outlook was;\nRetail food prices may average\na little higher in 1958, especially\nduring the first six months. This\nwill be partly because of the strong\ndemand for some foods that will be\nin shorter supply, such as beef and\neggs, and partly because marketing\ncharges will be higher. When costs\nof getting food from farm to gro\ncery store rise, the increases are\nlikely to show up in retail prices.\nTotal meat supplies next year\nwill be close to the near-record\nhigh of 1957, but there will be a\nlarger share of pork and a smaller\nshare of beef and veal. Retail\nprices of meat may average higher\n\u2014at least until midyear when the\nheavier supplies of pork start com\ning to market.\nMore chicken will be eaten. In\nfact, the outlook report said, chick\nconsumption in 1958 is expected\nto be record large. The increase\nwill be in commercial broilers. Tur\nkey consumption next year is ex\npected to be about the same as the\nrecord consumption of 1957. Retail\nprices of chicken are not expect\ned to average higher\u2014but egg\nprices are due fror a rise over 1957\nprices. There will be fewer eggs,\nat least to late summer, with fewer\nlaying hens.\nMilk production is expected to\n\u2022n\nbuoyed up by a rapidly growing\npopulation; a prospective increase\nrather than decrease in Federal\nGovernment expenditures for na\ntional defense; almost certain con\ntinued increases in expenditures\nby state and local governments;\nthe probability of sustained resi\ndential construction at current\nrates, assisted by an easier money\npolicy; and the prevalence of high\nlevels, even if not new records, in\nnumerous business indices. More\nover, the optimists point out that\nsuch adjustments as have already\ntaken place and are continuing to\ntake place are confined largely to\nthe durable goods industries where\nadjustments are due or overdue;\nand what is superficially interpret\ned as bad news; is in reality a\nhealthy correction for past ex\ncesses.\nHasty an&logies are already be\ning mad 3 between the current state\nof affairs and the 1953-1954, or the\n1948-1949 readjustments and the\n1937-1938 recession, insinuating\nthat we are in for something like\none of -hose bumps.\nComparisons with former periods\nare tantalizing, but not very useful\nfor purposes of forecasting. The\nsurrounding conditions are always\nso different. Business never was\nprecisely like it is at present and,\nwhatever it is, we have to put up\nwith it as best we can. There is\nreally no good cause for alarm or\ncomplacency. Both the pessimists\nand the optimists might be wrong.\nDoes it not appear that a middle\nof-the-road position would be the*\nmost sensible attitude under the\ncircumstances? Why not make a\nfrank acknowledgment that we are\nnavigating a slightly rougher sea,\nencountering more shoals, higher\nwinds, and perplexing cross cur\nrents; that the sellers' market has\nbeen replaced by a buyers' market;\nthat jobs are no longer quite so\nplentiful as they have been recent\nly; that it is harder to earn net\nprofits?\nWell-seasoned businessmen have\ngone through such times before and\nare more or less prepared. They\nare prepared to face additional ad\nversity if it comes, or renewed\nbusiness activity if it should come.\nThere is, however, a younger gen\neration of businessmen who are\nperhaps tasting a bit of rough wea\nther for the first time and they may\nscare easily.\nThere is no foregone conclusion\n(a) that we have sailed into the\nedge of a major storm, or (b) that\nwe have encountered only a mere\nsquall that will soon blow over. No\none really knows; but every busi\nnessman know T s how to be prepared\nfor either eventuality without ad\nvice from us. We shall continue to\nwatch and report on the changing\nweather and wish all our readers\ngood cruising.\nincreas' next year. Retail prices of\nmilk and dairy products are not\nexpected to change much.\nLarge supplies of processed fruits\nand vegetables will be on markets\nthrough the winter and spring\nmonths. Gi' en average weather in\nsouthern growing areas, winter\nand spring markets should have\ngood supplies of fresh vegetables.\nThere will be more apples, oranges,\nand grapefruit on markets in win\nter and spring months than last\nyear.\nGlamorize Left-Over Turkey\nMake hot turkey salad to glam\norize the meat for your holiday en\ntertaining and family dinners.\nBaked chicken salad originated\nin Delaware, and it's delicious\nmade with turkey. For a company\nluncheon, feature the salad with\ngreen peas or broccoli, cranberry\nsauce, hot rolls, and a festive des\nsert of plum pudding or pecan tart\u00ea.\nThis recipe serves six to eight:\n2 cups chopped turkey\n2 cups diced celery\n1 cup toasted bread cubes\n1 cup toasted almonds\nteaspoon salt\n2 teaspoons grated onion\n1 cup mayonnaise\n2 tablespoons lemon juice\n14 cup grated cheese\ncup toasted bread crumbs\nCombine all but the last two in\ngredients. Pile lightly into baking\ndish. Then sprinkle with cheese\nand break crumbs. Bake in 450 de\ngree oven for 25 to 30 minutes,\nridgeWAY, S. C. (IP)\nRidgeway resident returned from\nEngland with what is believed to\ne one D f the oldest bicycles in\nexistence.\nRobert W. Metcalfe baid a Pari\nsian manufacturer, Pierre Michaux,\napparently developed the bicycle\nabout 1851. It -vas known in France\nas a velocipede and later in Eng\nland as a \"boneshaker\".\n\nOLD \"BONESHAKER*'\nA\n.{C\nC\u00dc\nUC/\nno\nm\ny 6\nI\nAC\n\nit\nV\nfsei\nr\nr,.\n\ny\n\u00abs\ng\nV\nPi\nJ\n:y :M\nsSs\n\nSEASON\nEND\nBARGAINS\n1957 MERCURY Contclair 4-Dr. Hardtop\nThis car has everything\u2014 P\u00f4wer steering\u2014 power brakes\nradio\u2014heater\u2014white walls.\n1956 BUICK Super 4-Dr. Hardtop\n\u00e0 one owner automobile with extremely low mileage\nthat has been given meticulous care. Fully equipped\nincluding power steering, power brakes, tinted glass,\nwhite wall tires, 4-way power seat, custom interior.\n\n1955 OLDSMOBILE 4-Dr. Sedan Super 88\nOne owner, hydramatic, radio, heat\u00e8r, very clean, low\nmileage, excellent mechanical condition.\n1953 BUICK 4-Dr. Special\nI\nDynaflow, radio, heater, white walls, exceptionally\nclean, just traded on 58 Buick.\nI\n1955 FORD 6 cylinder\nStraight gear, heater, very clean, low mileage, eco\nnomical to run.\n1953 CHEVROLET 210 Series\nPowerglide, Radio and heater.\n1953 FORD V-8 4-Dr.\nRadio, heater, one owner, clean.\n1952 BUICK Super Riviera\nStraight transmission, radio and heater, excellent\nmechanical condition.\n1951 CHEVROLET 2-Dr. Sedan\nRadio and heater, just traded on Buick by local owner.\n1953 FORD Station Wagon\nFordomotic, radio, heater, excellent condition, traded\nby local owner.\n\n1950 BUICK\nOne owner, straight transmission.\n1948 CADILLAC 2-Dr.\nHydramatic, radio, heater, white walls, very clean,\ngood mechanical condition.\nKent Sussex Motor Co.\nNorth East Front St. Rehoboth Blvd.\nTelephone 8011 or 4326\nMilford, Delaware\nOPEN EVERY EVENING, MONDAY-FRIOAY, 7-f","height":"25059","width":"20160"}}
